    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title><jats:p>Utilizing evidence from literary stylistics, and in keeping with the Kachruvian tradition, this paper makes the case for WE scholars to remain vigilant of the move away from the revolutionary heteroglossia and de\u2010Englishing strategies hallmarking literary creation and analyses of postcolonial writings from the margin \u2013 so apparent in Braj B. Kachru's works \u2013 to a current era of monoglossic inspired re\u2010Englishing strategies underpinning the post\u2010globalist enterprise of so\u2010called \u2018flat\u2010world\u2019 fiction in which under the guise of linguistic deterritorialization, center and periphery stratificational and spatialized arrangements emerge somewhat mitigated \u2013 even obfuscated. In the current post\u2010structuralist\u2010turn where contextual\u2010oriented rather than form\u2010focused analyses and the \u2018spatial turn\u2019 prevail, it is contested, Kachruvian\u2010spotlighted linguistic asymmetries<jats:italic>still</jats:italic>matter. Evidence is provided from emerging frameworks in the sociolinguistics of mobility, pedagogical linguistics, and political economy to demonstrate the intellectual staying power, and relevancy of Kachruvian frameworks for current sociolinguists.</jats:p>",
